# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zero-trust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] It was created in response to the 2009 Operation Aurora.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] An open source implementation inspired by Google's research paper on an access proxy is known as "transcend".
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Google documented its Zero Trust journey from 2014 to 2018 through a series of articles in the journal ;login:.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Google called their ZT network "BeyondCorp".
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Google implemented a Zero Trust architecture on a large scale, and relied on user and device credentials, regardless of location.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Data was encrypted and protected from managed devices.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Unmanaged devices, such as BYOD, were not given access to the BeyondCorp resources.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp utilized a zero trust security model, which is a relatively new security model that it assumes that all devices and users are potentially compromised.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] This is in contrast to traditional security models, which rely on firewalls and other perimeter defenses to protect sensitive data.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The corporate network grants no inherent trust, and all internal apps are accessed via the BeyondCorp system, regardless of whether the user is in a Google office or working remotely.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp is related to Zero Trust architecture as it implements a true Zero Trust network, where all access is granted on identity, device, and authentication, based on robust underlying device and identity data sources.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp works by using a number of security policies including authentication, authorization, and access control to ensure that only authorized users can access corporate resources.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Authentication verifies the identity of the user, authorization determines whether the user has permission to access the requested resource, and access control policies restrict what the user can do with the resource.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] One of the main components in BeyondCorp's implementation is the Trust Inferrer.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The Trust Inferrer is a security component (typically software) that looks at information about a user's device, like a computer or phone, to decide how much it can be trusted to access certain resources like important company documents.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The Trust Inferrer checks things like the security of the device, whether it has the right software installed, and if it belongs to an authorized user.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Based on all this information, the Trust Inferrer decides what the device can access and what it can't.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Unlike traditional VPNs, BeyondCorp's access policies are based on information about a device, its state, and its associated user.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp considers both internal networks and external networks to be completely untrusted, and gates access to applications by dynamically asserting and enforcing levels, or “tiers,” of access.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp utilized a Device Inventory Database and Device Identity that uniquely identifies a device through a digital certificate.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Any changes to the device are recorded in the Device Inventory Database.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The certificate is used to uniquely identify a device; however, additional information is required to grant access privileges to a resource.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Another important component of BeyondCorp's implementation is the Access Control Engine.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Think of this as the brain of the Zero Trust architecture.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The Access Control Engine is like a traffic cop standing at an intersection.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Its job is to make sure that only authorized devices and users are allowed to access specific resources (like files or applications) on the network.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] It checks the access policy (the rules that say who can access what), the device's state (like whether it has the right software updates or security settings), and the resources being requested.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] Then it makes a decision on whether to grant or deny access based on all of this information.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] It helps ensure that only the right people and devices are allowed access to the network, which helps keep things secure.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The Access Control Engine utilizes the output from the Trust Inferrer and other data that is fed into its system.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] One of the first things Google did to implement a Zero Trust architecture was to capture and analyze network traffic.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] The purpose of analyzing the traffic was to build a baseline of what typical network traffic looked like.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] In doing so, BeyondCorp also discovered unusual, unexpected, and unauthorized traffic.
[src:zero-trust/beyondcorp] This was very useful because it gave the BeyondCorp engineers critical information that assisted them in reengineering the system in a secure manner.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] The idea behind the defense in depth approach is to defend a system against any particular attack using several independent methods.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] It is a layering tactic, conceived by the National Security Agency (NSA) as a comprehensive approach to information and electronic security.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth is sometimes thought of as forming the layers of an onion, with data at the core of the onion, people the next outer layer of the onion, and network security, host-based security, and application security forming the outermost layers of the onion.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth can be divided into three overarching areas: Physical, Technical, and Administrative.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Physical controls are anything that physically limits or prevents access to IT systems.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of physical defensive security are: fences, guards, dogs, and CCTV systems.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Technical controls are hardware or software whose purpose is to protect systems and resources.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of technical controls include disk encryption, file integrity software, authentication, network security controls, antiviruses, and behavioural analysis software.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] In the event that one layer of defence fails, defense in depth aims to ensure network security via a second-line of defence.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] For example, if an attacker penetrates a computer system at a given OSI layer (e.g.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Layer 3), a redundancy should exist at another layer (Layer 7) to ensure layered defense.
[src:zero-trust/defense-in-depth-computing] Administrative controls are the organization's policies and procedures and govern the organisation's human resources, technology, and operations.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Network security starts with authentication, commonly with a username and a password.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Since this requires just one detail authenticating the user name—i.e., the password—this is sometimes termed one-factor authentication.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] With two-factor authentication, something the user 'has' is also used (e.g., a security token or 'dongle', an ATM card, or a mobile phone); and with three-factor authentication, something the user 'is' is also used (e.g., a fingerprint or retinal scan).
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Once authenticated, a firewall enforces access policies such as what services are allowed to be accessed by the network users.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Though effective to prevent unauthorized access, this component may fail to check potentially harmful content such as computer worms or Trojans being transmitted over the network.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Anti-virus software or an intrusion prevention system (IPS) help detect and inhibit the action of such malware.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] An anomaly-based intrusion detection system may also monitor the network like wireshark traffic and may be logged for audit purposes and for later high-level analysis.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Newer systems combining unsupervised machine learning with full network traffic analysis can detect active network attackers from malicious insiders or targeted external attackers that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Communication between two hosts using a network may be encrypted to maintain security and privacy.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Honeypots, essentially decoy network-accessible resources, may be deployed in a network as surveillance and early-warning tools, as the honeypots are not normally accessed for legitimate purposes.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Honeypots are placed at a point in the network where they appear vulnerable and undefended, but they are actually isolated and monitored.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Techniques used by the attackers that attempt to compromise these decoy resources are studied during and after an attack to keep an eye on new exploitation techniques.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Such analysis may be used to further tighten security of the actual network being protected by the honeypot.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] A honeypot can also direct an attacker's attention away from legitimate servers.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] A honeypot encourages attackers to spend their time and energy on the decoy server while distracting their attention from the data on the real server.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Similar to a honeypot, a honeynet is a network set up with intentional vulnerabilities.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Its purpose is also to invite attacks so that the attacker's methods can be studied and that information can be used to increase network security.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] A honeynet typically contains one or more honeypots.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Previous research on network security was mostly about using tools to secure transactions and information flow, and how well users knew about and used these tools.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] However, more recently, the discussion has expanded to consider information security in the broader context of the digital economy and society.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] This is indicative of network security topics covering not just individual users and tools, but also conversations about the larger culture of information security in our digital world.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Security management for networks is different for all kinds of situations.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] A home or small office may only require basic security while large businesses may require high-maintenance and advanced software and hardware to prevent malicious attacks from hacking and spamming.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] In order to minimize susceptibility to malicious attacks from external threats to the network, corporations often employ tools which carry out network security verifications.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] These tools can also mitigate and detect internal human behavior such as insider threats and email storms.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] The human element is often the weakest link in any network security system, as evidenced by a study in 2014 which found that employees often do not see themselves as part of their organization's information security effort and often take actions that impede organizational changes.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] The move from centralized systems to cloud-based and hybrid work environments has made it harder to monitor networks, especially with traditional tools.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] A Broadcom survey found that 65% of respondents rely on third-party network providers, which creates blind spots and makes systems more vulnerable.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Dependence on third parties also reduces an organization's direct control over its network infrastructure, making it harder to implement advanced monitoring processes.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Networks are subject to attacks from malicious sources.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] Attacks can be from one of two categories: *passive* and *active*.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] A passive attack occurs when a malicious actor intercepts data traveling across a network, usually without generating any kind of alerts.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] It can be difficult or impossible to know if this kind of attack has occurred.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] For example, a wardriving attack can wirelessly detect the four-way handshake between an access point and a client, and crack the password offline without the owner of the access point ever knowing.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] An active attack occurs when a malicious actor initiates commands targeting the network or network resources.
[src:zero-trust/network-security] This is generally meant to disrupt the network's normal operation, conduct reconnaissance, or attempt lateral movements to find and gain access to assets available via the network.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:zero-trust/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] A **software-defined perimeter** (**SDP**), sometimes referred to as a **black cloud**, is a network architecture used to implement zero-trust principles.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The SDP specification was developed by the Cloud Security Alliance (CSA) to control resource access based on identity.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] In an SDP, connectivity follows a need-to-know model, requiring both entity authentication and device posture validation before granting access to internal assets.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The application infrastructure is effectively "black", a term used by the United States Department of Defense to describe undetectable infrastructure, as it lacks visible DNS information or IP addresses.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Traditional enterprise network architecture is based on the premise of an internal network isolated by a fixed perimeter, typically consisting of firewalls.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] These firewalls block external entities from accessing internal assets while allowing the internal users to connect to external resources.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] However, the proliferation of user-managed devices, remote connectivity, SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS has extended the perimeter and broadened the attack surface.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Software-Defined Perimeters (SDPs) address these issues by allowing application owners to deploy perimeters that maintain the traditional model's invisibility and inaccessibility.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Unlike static firewalls, SDPs can be deployed anywhere—on the internet, in the cloud, at a hosting center, on a private corporate network, or across some or all of these locations.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] There are several techniques for delivering a software-defined perimeter.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] In its simplest form, the SDP architecture consists of two components: SDP Hosts and SDP Controllers.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] SDP Hosts can either initiate or accept connections.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Interactions with the SDP Controllers manage these actions through a control channel (see Figure 1).
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] As a result, the control plane is separated from the data plane in an SDP, enabling greater scalability.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Additionally, all components can be made redundant for higher availability.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] One or more accepting SDP Hosts are brought online.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] These hosts connect to and authenticate with the controllers.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] However, they do not acknowledge communication from any other host and will not respond to any non-provisioned requests.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Each Initiating SDP Host that comes online connects to and authenticates with the SDP Controllers.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] After authenticating the Initiating SDP Host, the SDP Controllers determine a list of Accepting SDP Hosts with which the initiating host is authorized to communicate.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The SDP Controller instructs the Accepting SDP Hosts to accept communication from the Initiating SDP Host and applies any optional policies required for encrypted communications.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The SDP Controller provides the Initiating SDP Host with the list of Accepting SDP Hosts and any optional policies required for encrypted communications.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The Initiating SDP Host establishes a mutual VPN connection with all authorized Accepting SDP Hosts.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] While the general workflow remains the same for all implementations, the application of SDPs can favour certain implementations over others.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] In the client-to-gateway implementation, one or more servers are protected behind an Accepting SDP Host, which acts as a gateway between the clients and the protected servers.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] This implementation can be used within an enterprise network to mitigate common lateral movement attacks, such as server scanning, OS and application vulnerability exploits, password cracking, man-in-the-middle attacks, pass-the-hash (PtH) and others.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Alternatively, it can be implemented on the internet to isolate protected servers from unauthorized users and mitigate attacks.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The client-to-server implementation offers features and benefits similar to the client-to-gateway implementation.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] However, in a client-to-server scenario, the protected server runs the Accepting SDP Host software rather than using a gateway in front of the server running that software.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The choice between the client-to-gateway and client-to-server implementations is typically based on factors such as the number of servers being protected, load balancing methods, server elasticity, and other topological considerations.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] For example, the server initiating the REST call would be the Initiating SDP Host, and the server offering the REST service would be the Accepting SDP Host.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Implementing an SDP for this use case can reduce the load on these services and mitigate attacks similar to those mitigated by the client-to-gateway implementation.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] The client-to-server-to-client implementation creates a peer-to-peer relationship between the two clients and can be used for applications such as IP telephony, chat and video conferencing.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] In these cases, the SDP obfuscates the IP addresses of the connecting clients.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Alternatively, a client-to-gateway-to-client configuration can hide the application server as well.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] In the context of data breaches involving intellectual property, financial records, and human resources data, attackers typically gain initial entry by compromising a single endpoint.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] Following the initial breach, they exploit the network's flat architecture to move laterally, seeking access to high-value information assets.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] To counter this threat, organizations can deploy a Software-Defined Perimeter (SDP) within the data center to partition the network and isolate sensitive applications.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] By enforcing access controls, the SDP restricts unauthorized access to protected resources.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] This prevents the lateral movement necessary for large-scale data exfiltration, localizing the breach and securing the enterprise's most critical data.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] As the proliferation of interconnected devices increases, the back-end applications responsible for managing these devices and processing sensitive data have become mission-critical.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] SDPs enhance the security and availability of these systems by concealing servers and their communication from the public internet.
[src:zero-trust/software-defined-perimeter] This "dark" infrastructure approach prevents unauthorized discovery and targeted external attacks.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] ZTA is implemented by establishing identity verification, validating device compliance prior to granting access, and ensuring least privilege access to only explicitly-authorized resources.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] Most modern corporate networks consist of many interconnected zones, cloud services and infrastructure, connections to remote and mobile environments, and connections to non-conventional IT, such as IoT devices.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The traditional approach by trusting users and devices within a notional "corporate perimeter" or via a VPN connection is commonly not sufficient in the complex environment of a corporate network.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The zero trust architecture has been proposed for use in specific areas such as supply chains.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The principles of zero trust can be applied to data access, and to the management of data.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] This brings about zero trust data security where every request to access the data needs to be authenticated dynamically and ensure least privileged access to resources.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In order to determine if access can be granted, policies can be applied based on the attributes of the data, who the user is, and the type of environment using Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC).
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] This zero trust data security approach can protect access to the data.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] Several definitions of zero trust have been proposed since the term was first used in 1994.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In April 1994, the term "zero trust" was coined by Stephen Paul Marsh in his doctoral thesis on computer security at the University of Stirling.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] Marsh's work studied trust as something finite that can be described mathematically, asserting that the concept of trust transcends human factors such as morality, ethics, lawfulness, justice, and judgement.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The problems of the Smartie or M&M model of the network (the precursor description of de-perimeterisation) was described by a Sun Microsystems engineer in a Network World article in May 1994, who described firewalls' perimeter defence, as a hard shell around a soft centre, like a Cadbury Egg.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In 2001 the first version of the OSSTMM (Open Source Security Testing Methodology Manual) was released and this had some focus on trust.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] Version 3 which came out around 2007 has a whole chapter on Trust which says "Trust is a Vulnerability" and talks about how to apply the OSSTMM 10 controls based on Trust levels.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In 2018, the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and National Cybersecurity Center of Excellence (NCCoE) published NIST SP 800-207 – zero trust architecture.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The publication defines zero trust as a collection of concepts and ideas designed to reduce the uncertainty in enforcing accurate, per-request access decisions in information systems and services in the face of a network viewed as compromised.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] A Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) is an enterprise's cyber security plan that utilizes zero trust concepts and encompasses component relationships, workflow planning, and access policies.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] Therefore, a zero trust enterprise is the network infrastructure (physical and virtual) and operational policies that are in place for an enterprise as a product of a zero trust architecture plan.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology**.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The ZT-Kipling methodology moves beyond the foundational principles of Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) by defining a set of five mandatory, iterative steps.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] This methodology treats ZT as a continual and iterative process..
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] The core of the methodology’s systematic nature lies in its integration of the Kipling Criteria: what, why, when, where, who, and how.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] This entire process is repeated throughout the lifetime of a protected surface, which must be clearly defined in Step #1 of the methodology.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] TS 104 102 establishes the ZT-Kipling methodology as a systematic and cyclical governance framework for Zero Trust.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In 2010 the term Zero Trust model was used by analyst John Kindervag of Forrester Research to denote stricter cybersecurity programs and access control within corporations.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In 2003 the challenges of defining the perimeter to an organisation's IT systems was highlighted by the Jericho Forum, discussing the trend of what was then given the name "de-perimeterisation".
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In response to Operation Aurora, a Chinese APT attack throughout 2009, Google started to implement a zero-trust architecture referred to as BeyondCorp an internal initiative to implement a zero trust security model that eliminated the need for a privileged VPN.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] Throughout the 2010s, zero trust architectures became more prevalent, driven in part by increased adoption of mobile and cloud services.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In 2019 the United Kingdom National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) recommended that network architects consider a Zero Trust approach for new IT deployments, particularly where significant use of cloud services is planned.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In the United States, Executive Order 14028 (May 2021) directed federal agencies to adopt zero trust architectures, and the Office of Management and Budget subsequently issued memorandum M-22-09 requiring agencies to meet specific zero trust security goals by the end of fiscal year 2024.
[src:zero-trust/zero-trust-architecture] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology** to be used to achieve Zero Trust security posture.
